59th Vending machine of Mother Tunare <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> Terris Thule Server <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=208499">My Magely Equipment</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=noonievioletskies>NoonieVioletskies</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1533<br> <font color=#333333>(1/8/03 9:33:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=95>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sebminas.com/eq/baby.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> Sigh well i might as well give my real thoughts on this issue. Inc real long post.<br>
<br>
Few of us seem to recognize the real underlying issue with charm. Charm is not merely &quot;unbalanced&quot;, like how class01's nuke might be a little too good compared to class02, or class03's heal is too weak compared to class02; its a little bigger than that. The whole core design of the spell is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>broken</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, and the foundation of the spell must be redesigned.<br>
Despite what many of us think, its not the pop environment (mob strength, or potential risk) which makes charm broken. As i will explain later in my post, these things merely agrivate an existing issue. Saying pop made charm overpowered, is like blaming the salt for causing the wound. In practically every other instance, pop is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fine</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and most would agree is a step up from previous environments. Much like the salt, there is only an issue when it is introduced to the real problem -- design flaws inherent in the charm ability.<br>
<br>
First let me explain something which is essential to discussion. The game is nothing more than 3 elements, it is paying customers (the players) overcoming computer generated challenges (environments), for rewards (character advancement). This is pve, this is the game. Even on pvp servers this is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>still</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the game, you are only as good at pvp as you are at pve, since advancement is awarded through environmental progress only. The act of advancing is truly what defines a game, without it everquest is a chat room with computer generated scenery. Pvp in eq is a side event that one engages in just for fun, to settle disputes, whatever, between pve'ing. <br>
The problem as i see it is charm in its current incarnation takes two things which are at the foundation of the game <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>created</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for competition, and makes them no longer competitors. This has a whole spectrum of game breaking repercussion. Keep in mind im not saying physically turning a mob into an ally is broken, the act itself is neutral. Its allowing classes to actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>harness</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the full potential of mobs -- environmental <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>challenges</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> -- completely <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>unchecked</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> save for level restrictions <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>is</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> whats broken. At the heart of the matter, unpoliced meshing of environmental challenges and player ability is whats causing the problem. The problem is somewhat complex in nature, and is defined most prominantly by the following aspects:<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1) Charm makes the creation of dynamic content virtually impossible.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Current charm was created with one type of environment in mind. An environment where mobs are only a little stronger than players, in which leveling is an endless treadmill of non challenging mobs, and death, although rare carries a heavy penalty. This type of environment was pretty much the mold for previous expansions. Although arguably too powerful for a non-tanking, non-offensive class, charm really wasnt <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>broken</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> then. In some zones it was (kael being the biggest offender), but throughout most of norrath charm wasnt crazy like it is now. <br>
However, pop was designed a little differently than previous everquest expansions. Mobs are now rather difficult, but you kill a bit less of them. Also death penalties are lessened significantly. This has the side-effect of making charmed pets relatively much stronger than they ever have been before, while simultaneously mitigating the risk to the point where the rewards completely overwhelm it. <br>
As i said earlier, since charm fuses together 2 elements (players and environment) which by definition <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should be merged in such a way, the design of pop accentuates inherent flaws in the charm spell. This new high difficulty - low penalty environment didnt make charm broken; charm <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always was broken</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it just merely made the problem more obvious to everyone. <br>
<br>
The bottom line is, it was foolish of verant to allow an ability to scale with environmental difficulty like that, and it must be changed. Just as complete heal needed to be changed since it indirectly allowed class strength to scale with environmental difficulty, so is it now time to deal with charm and do the same. A hard coded limitation on charm must be created, and soon. The only other options are to: <br>
a) eliminate dynamic content and make all mobs of a certain level the same strength, and revert to the low blue leveling treadmill of previous expansions (which would negatively effect ALL players, even charm classes), or <br>
b) continue to allow charm classes to trample over everything in their path (this is not really an option, more like wishful thinking on behalf of a few selfish players).<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2) Charm is balanced in a world which assumes level is an appropriate indicator of difficulty of an encounter. </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
This is in the same vein as point #1, but is so important it should be elaborated on. I think a common mistake players make is to assume charm was supposed to be balanced <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>exclusively</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by potential risk, more specifically, the bigger of a mob you charm the more risk you expose yourself to. Most believe charm was intended to be balanced by the reward itself. Closer observation of the charm line proves this was probably <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the intention of the designer, since charm spells are capped by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>level</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. If charm was intended to be balanced by risk, and verant intended on enchanters being able to charm mobs which potentially could be overwhelmingly powerful, why then the level cap? I mean, shouldnt a level 50 enchanter be able to try his hand at charming a level 60 mob, since after all the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>risk</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should keep it balanced?<br>
<br>
But wait, a level 50 enchanter really <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cant</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> attempt to charm a 60 mob, because his charm spell has a level cap (i think its L52 isnt it?). The level caps function in the charm line as basically saying &quot;a level 50 enchanter should not have access to the kind of power that charming a level 60 mob would bring, regardless of risk&quot;. The level caps on charm spells <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>prove</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> verant never intended on charm being balanced by risk primarily, and they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>did</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> intend on their being hard coded limitations on the strength of what enchanters could charm.<br>
<br>
Now, heres where verant went wrong. Verant assumed that level alone was an appropriate indicator of mob strength, and this was a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>major</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> failing on their part.<br>
Charm currently is balanced only in a world where all L10, L20, L55, L56, L70, and ect mobs are x amount as strong. Unfortunately this world is not norrath, and never will be norrath, which is why charm has become more balanced by risk and less by level. Charm in its current state can only exist and be called balanced, or at least balanceable, in a non-dynamic world where the level of all content tells you the whole story about its difficulty. What the con system doesnt consider is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">reward</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, and this is a very important facet of environmental difficulty. <br>
A level 55 mob that drops very good loot (extra reward, extra incentive) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>should and will</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be stronger than a level 55 mob that drops standard coin loot. The better the loot, the more undercon the mob. Naggy, for example, is much stronger than mobs of his level. Kael giants are a little stronger than mobs of their level, since they have the potential to drop good quest pieces. There are endless examples of &quot;under-con&quot; mobs who are more challenging for appropriate level players than they should be, because of extra reward. <br>
<br>
So you see, charm either must be rebalanced so that there is a more hard-capped potential from charming, or dynamic content must be done away with. Which would you prefer happen?<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3) Charm has grown to be balanced primarily around assumed limitations like risk, which just isnt enough compared to the potential the spell offers.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Even though evidence shows this probably wasnt the intention of the original designer of the charm line, as everquest has matured and content has become more dynamic and varied as the game expands, this has become the case. Now charm is balanced less by hard coded restriction like level, and more by assumed restrictions like potential risk from mob difficulty. This just <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is not appropriate</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for an ability as powerful as charm. It is more not appropriate for a class with by far the best ability to mitigate the dps of their enemies, to have an ability which is self policed like that. Enchanters are capable of mitigating nearly all the &quot;risk&quot; their pets pose. <br>
<br>
The conclusion is obvious. <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Charm must be redesigned so that there is a hard coded restriction on the power of their pets</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
This solution must keep in mind the following:<br>
-Charm still does have a risk attached to it, but risk should not be the primary balancing factor of the charm line. If an enchanter charms a more undercon L55 mob, his power should increase more than it would from charming an overcon L55 mob. Putting a flat damage/tanking limit on all 55 pets, 56 pets, ect should not be a solution.<br>
-Enchanters are not a dps class. They are not a tank. They are enchanters, theyre primary job is to reduce the dps of enemies through spells amongst other functions. Charm spells should not trivialize true dps classes and tank classes. Charm is supposed to be situational, and enchanters should not be able to maintain a charmed pet indefinitely.<br>
<br>
<br>
That said, i think the following changes to charm would make it more balanced.<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Attatch a resource-drain component to the spell which scales with level.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The resource drain component should be potent enough to mitigate the bonus of both level-appropriate clarity lines, and druid hp lines, as well as bring the caster into a deficit over time. Class specific abilities should be brought into consideration, for example the mage spell would drain a little more hp than others, the necro version would drain alot more mana, ect. The desired result is that the caster cannot maintain a charmed pet for more than a few minutes.<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Attatch a recast delay to all charm spells.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> This way, should you desire to keep a mob perma charmed it would take the collective efforts of more than one caster. You <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>can</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> still utilize the full strength of the mob, but it does not belong to one character. If it took 4 enchanters and a cleric to do what 1 good enchanter does currently, that would be fair. The goal is so the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>individual dps</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of all 5 characters would be less than the individual dps of a mage or rogue.<br>
<br>
Thoughts? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=noonievioletskies>NoonieVioletskies</A> at: 1/8/03 9:55:53 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=terrato686>Terrato686</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#333333>(1/8/03 10:14:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=96>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> Well said Noonie =) <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://pluto.imagemagician.com/images/terrato686/Bluex2xx3x.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=364086">Archmage of Zeb</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lordgojirax>LordGojirax</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Conjurer</span><br>  Posts: 269<br> <font color=#333333>(1/8/03 11:41:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=97>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.jackntracie.com/images/gojhead.jpg width=98 height=126></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> Well, I read that whole thing and I commend you on your efforts to come up with an alternative, not that I agree with it in it's entirety.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Risk isn't the only factor.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
It takes a great deal of risk as has been pointed out.<br>
<br>
It also takes a horrendous amount of mana and time to do succesfuly. (And success is NEVER a guaranteed thing, in fact, you are more likely to fail than succeed when charming.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Methods by which Charm is managed by the developers:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
- Some mobs are flagged &quot;Immune&quot; to charm.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>When Verant tuned resists for Mobs, that allowed them to be nuked or cast on, but set their resistance to certain spells individualy... they have all the tools they need now to tune each event to have fully dynamic content.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Level isn't the only limiting factor.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
- Magic resistance is a huge factor.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Mobs get a resistance check against charm every 6 seconds. (The higher the mobs MR, the more likely he will be to break charm. Thus, a level 55 mob with LOW MR will stay charmed much longer than one with a HIGH MR. (This means level isn't the only governing factor.)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The exact and simple answer is to tune encounters and zones. They've had the ability to do this for quite some time now. There are a HUGE number of things in the game that the developers had never considered when making this game. Feign Death was just supposed to be a way for Monks to escape death, it was never intended to be a tool for pulling mobs.<br>
<br>
Just because the players find a way to use the spells and skills in new and creative ways doesn't mean they shouldn't have it, and it doesn't mean it's &quot;Broken&quot;. It just means they need to take the next step and make sure the content can adapt to things like this.<br>
<br>
In only the most extreme situations (Like Mod Rods and Complete Heal, which, unlike Charming had NO risk and were guaranteed positive results infinitely.) should a spell or ability be reduced or removed. Charm isn't one of them. Tune the content, not the spell, and most of the content is fine the way it is.<br>
<br>
Enchanters are NOT defined as crowd controllers. Your definition is incorrect there. They are masters of Mind and Body control. They buff your minds and bodies, while boggling the minds and bodies of those that would harm them. This includes charming, as well as mezmerizing and slowing them.<br>
<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.jackntracie.com/images/gojirax.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lordgojirax>LordGojirax</A> at: 1/8/03 11:42:05 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2624<br> <font color=#333333>(1/9/03 1:49:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=98>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Well &quot;Pet Centered Groups&quot; are putting tanks out of a job and that's just as wrong in my opinion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I have seen this non-sequitor put forth too many times now to be amused any more.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Pet-Centered Groups</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are an alternate group form that in no way threatens the groupability of any class.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>CoD</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->-chanters with ubiquitous charmed mobs dealing in excess of 400 DPS are a threat to every damage dealing class in every group, regardless of style.<br>
<br>
Suppose you have a group, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">any</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> group, with one open slot.  Suppose you have a choice to fill that last slot with a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>CoD</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->-chanter, mage, wizard, rogue, ranger, or monk.<br>
<br>
Is there any reason <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">not</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to choose the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>CoD</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->-chanter?  They will do at least twice the damage of any of the other choices.<br>
<br>
The whole <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;oh my pet groups invalidate tanks&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> fallacy is grasping at straws.<br>
<br>
The one thing I do not see in these threads that I saw in the earlier referenced threads are proposed solutions that minimize the impact on the enchanter class.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=noonievioletskies>NoonieVioletskies</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1536<br> <font color=#333333>(1/9/03 4:00:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=99>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sebminas.com/eq/baby.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Well, I read that whole thing and I commend you on your efforts to come up with an alternative, not that I agree with it in it's entirety.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
thanks<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Risk isn't the only factor.<br>
It takes a great deal of risk as has been pointed out.<br>
<br>
It also takes a horrendous amount of mana and time to do succesfuly. (And success is NEVER a guaranteed thing, in fact, you are more likely to fail than succeed when charming.)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well yes there are other balancing factors for the charm line of course, such as invested time and mana reserves, but they are so nominal relative to the reward that they are barely worth aknowledging. Let me better illustrate what i mean.<br>
<br>
Lets assume that the average CoD pet lasts 5 minutes. Sure some pets will break in 5 seconds and some will last the whole duration, but on average a pet is maintained for 5 minutes. Just to be clear this is a mythical, although realistic figure.<br>
<br>
CoD costs 700 mana per cast, and it is in an enchanters main spec. Its probably not unreasonable to assume this enchanter has scm 3 which is a total mana reduction of i think 23%. The spell costs about 540 mana then. <br>
Also, lets assume the enchanter refreshes their arcane rune (400m) every charm break. This is a spell in a secondary spec, which would put mana savings at about 13%, i think. Total mana cost is now  888 per charm. <br>
And finally lets assume the enchanter throws out a word of morrell, in addition to rune, to further mitigate ex pet damage. This is also a secondary spec spell, which now brings the total mana cost to 1149 per charm break.<br>
<br>
1149 mana over the course of 5 minutes is 23 mana/tic. You might be thinking thats alot, but lets look at this a little further, shall we? Closer inspection reveals thats not alot at all, and for the rewards it is in fact outrageously mana efficient.<br>
<br>
Most charmed pets in pop do 250 dps and up. Lets say you are in a group which lasts 2 hours, with 70% uptime, and your pet does 250 dps (a modest figure btw). So, that means the enchanter did 250 dps every second, for 5,040 seconds for a total of 1,260,000 damage. The enchanter spends about 27,600 points of mana over the course of 2 hours to do this damage. This is a damage:mana ratio of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>46</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. That is close to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>ten times</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> better than the best wizard mana:damage ratios -- wizards, a pure offensive class are 10 times less efficient in dealing magical damage than an enchanter, a class whos purpose is to mitigate damage. How can you say the mana cost isnt nominal relative to the reward?<br>
<br>
The 23 mana/tic figure doesnt even realistically <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>interfere</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with an enchanters ability to do other tasks like cc and slow. With things like horses, c5, sd, ft, and what not 23 mana/tic is just a drop in the bucket. Another thing to keep in mind is this 23 mana/tic figure is hardly static. For one thing if pets on average last longer than 5 minutes, and im sure they do, mana spent is alot <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>lower</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than 23 per tic. Also enchanters dont need to spend all that mana on stuns and runes either, if they are grouped with a snare class, or if they have the aa rune skill, that alievates alot of the mana cost.<br>
<br>
Anyway, in short, my point is that charm in no way is realistically balanced by resources, relative to the damage of true offensive mana based classes, it is criminally efficient. It is almost entirely balanced around <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>risk</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, and you can see my first post as for my arguement of why it is not a good idea to balance charm around risk (difficulty with the creation of dynamic content, also a tendancy to over estimate associated risk since enchanters are so great at mitigating damage).<br>
<br>
And as for your arguement of charm taking alot of time... well seeing as the damage is done through an entity seperate from the enchanter, i fail to see the concern. A few seconds every few minutes to manage charm breaks is hardly &quot;alot of time&quot; and it really should not interefere with an enchanters ability to do other things like cc and support.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Methods by which Charm is managed by the developers:<br>
- Some mobs are flagged &quot;Immune&quot; to charm.<br>
When Verant tuned resists for Mobs, that allowed them to be nuked or cast on, but set their resistance to certain spells individualy... they have all the tools they need now to tune each event to have fully dynamic content.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You have a point, but the point you bring up just isnt good enough of a solution (flag more difficult mobs uncharmable). Mobs which yeild an extremely high reward (such as low con older expansion boss mobs) and therefore are huge undercons can always be flagged uncharmable, sure.<br>
<br>
...But what about more subtle, less obvious, variations in mob strength? Say you are in a ficticious dungeon with a 30% experiance bonus. Due to the increased reward relative to other mobs, it is expected the mobs be tougher. Should every type of mob in the zone be flagged uncharmable?<br>
<br>
My point is that undercon mobs *are everywhere*. Do you expect verant to keep in mind every little detail of this vast world, and flag all these mobs uncharmable, simply to avoid directly changing the way charm works? I just dont see that as a realistic option. <br>
Since charm directly utilizes the strength of the casters environment, there needs to be more hard coded limitations for the usage of such a powerful tool. The results of not doing this are evident everywhere -- enchanters soloing mobs which wipe out 2 full groups, enchanters soloing woushi (using undercon mobs), ect.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Level isn't the only limiting factor.<br>
- Magic resistance is a huge factor.<br>
Mobs get a resistance check against charm every 6 seconds. (The higher the mobs MR, the more likely he will be to break charm. Thus, a level 55 mob with LOW MR will stay charmed much longer than one with a HIGH MR. (This means level isn't the only governing factor.)<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You have a point, but this really falls into the &quot;risk&quot; vein of charm restrictions, which is subject to all the failings of other &quot;assumed risk&quot; type limiting factors. Charming a mob with higher than average mr is simply more risky, but there is not really a hard coded limitation which prevents you from doing it. All it means is you expose yourself to more risk, and your damage is a little less efficient.<br>
<br>
Like other types of risk, this is not an appropriate enough balancing factor for charm potential, because it can too easily be mitigated. Resists can be circumvented through tash and malise (the first is an innate enchanter ability which is virtually mana free, the later is usually readily accessable). Also it is worth mentioning CoD has a -50 resist mod.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The exact and simple answer is to tune encounters and zones. They've had the ability to do this for quite some time now. There are a HUGE number of things in the game that the developers had never considered when making this game. Feign Death was just supposed to be a way for Monks to escape death, it was never intended to be a tool for pulling mobs.<br>
<br>
Just because the players find a way to use the spells and skills in new and creative ways doesn't mean they shouldn't have it, and it doesn't mean it's &quot;Broken&quot;. It just means they need to take the next step and make sure the content can adapt to things like this.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
So basically what your saying is, dont nerf the ability. Adapt (aka nerf) the environment. I couldnt disagree with you more. Not only is it completely impractical for verant to go about and change aspects of all mobs, zone design, or whatever just to avoid simply nerfing some classes ability (which btw, would end up with the exact same result in the end -- the death of the overpowered action), but most of the time it hurts players <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>more</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to nerf an environment than it does to nerf <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>one</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> class(es) ability.<br>
<br>
For example, in order to &quot;adapt the environment&quot; to current charm the following actions would need to take place.<br>
1) Broader blue con range reintroduced. <br>
2) All appropriate leveling zones have mob frequency increased, but level and difficulty decreased.<br>
3) Mobs now yeild signifigantly less exp per kill.<br>
4) Harsher death penalties reintroduced.<br>
<br>
Both would result in the desired effect - charm pets no longer being ridiculously as strong as they are now. However, adapting (nerfing) the environment rather than directly nerfing the ability has a whole host of additional negative side affects which hurt <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> players, including the charmers. Just a few examples...<br>
<br>
1) Back to the exp treadmill, WOOT!<br>
2) Death sucks, again.<br>
3) Play being more tedious, leveling feeling more like work and less like fun.<br>
<br>
Which do you think players would prefer? Which do you think even charm classes would prefer?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
In only the most extreme situations (Like Mod Rods and Complete Heal, which, unlike Charming had NO risk and were guaranteed positive results infinitely.) should a spell or ability be reduced or removed. Charm isn't one of them. Tune the content, not the spell, and most of the content is fine the way it is.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I disagree, and i consider charm to very much be an extreme situation the calibur of mod rod and complete heal.<br>
<br>
First, &quot;assumed risk&quot; is very much over rated, esspecially when the class in question specilizes in dealing with emergancy situations and minimalizing dps. <br>
Second, both mod rod and ch had their own attatched risks. Mod rods lowered your health per use signifigantly, and ive not yet met a mage who hasnt killed themselves on them either due to a careless click or accidentally dropping below frenzy range. The more hp you heal from a ch, the more hate the cleric drew. <br>
Both came with their own risk. It isnt a question of whether or not risk is present. Risk is present in everything you do in eq really. Its whether or not the risk is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>sufficient</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for the reward. In the case of mod rods and ch, the risk wasnt even close to being sufficient. The same is true of charm, id say to an even greater degree than mod rod or ch.  <br>
<br>
Theres no way around it. The design of charm needs to be changed.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Enchanters are NOT defined as crowd controllers. Your definition is incorrect there. They are masters of Mind and Body control. They buff your minds and bodies, while boggling the minds and bodies of those that would harm them. This includes charming, as well as mezmerizing and slowing them.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well yea thats the rp spiel. <br>
<br>
Lets use mages as an example. Sure mages are summoners, we conjure things like rains of steel, bolts of lava, shields of flame, elemental companions, as well as jewelry imbued with magical power, loaves of bread, weightless bags, amongst other things. We summon (bring existing things to us) and conjure (create something from nothing) lots of stuff. <br>
The practical application of a mage though, is a potent damage dealer with minor utility and virtually no ability to mitigate damage.<br>
<br>
Enchanters deal with mental manipulation, sure. They stun, blind, fear, and drive there enemies to madness through their spells. However, the practical application of an enchanters abilities in eq has traditionally been in crowd control, or more basically as a class who mimimizes the dps of enemies through spells. Secondarily they support other classes through buffs and do a little damage directly with animations, charmed pets, nukes and dots. They also tend to have spells useful for trade skills.  <br>
<br>
Rp really doesnt mean much regarding actual game balance. Technically i could rp explain that im a mage who summons things, therefore i should be able to summon a 10 charge instant cast ch vial for 20 mana called &quot;vial of elemental rejuvination&quot;. Kinda silly way to justify abilities isnt it? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=menarion>Menarion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#333333>(1/9/03 4:06:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=100>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> Very well said Noonie.  Wish I could speak as eloquently on the subject. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=306743">Arkinon Ben'Dar</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
